 is also a step-up to colocalization about which you read a bit more in chapter 10. Right, so from the above we identified three independent hits: rs6802898, rs7901695, rs8050136. Let’s put them in a dataset with their chromosome and basepair position and create a list. rsID &lt;- c(&quot;rs6802898&quot;, &quot;rs7901695&quot;, &quot;rs8050136&quot;) CHR &lt;- as.integer(c(3, 10, 16)) BP &lt;- as.integer(c(12366207, 114744078, 52373776)) # BPend &lt;- c(12366207 + 500000, 114744078 + 500000, 52373776 + 500000) variant_list &lt;- data.frame(rsID, CHR, BP) variant_list ## rsID CHR BP ## 1 rs6802898 3 12366207 ## 2 rs7901695 10 114744078 ## 3 rs8050136 16 52373776 variants_of_interest &lt;- c(variant_list$rsID) variants_of_interest ## [1] &quot;rs6802898&quot; &quot;rs7901695&quot; &quot;rs8050136&quot; We can now take the filtered and prepared GWAS summary statistics, i.e. gwas_assoc_compl you created earlier in chapter 7, to draw three nice regional association plots around these variants. This file should contain the following: tibble [306,102 × 14] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame) $ SNP : chr [1:306102] &quot;rs10000010&quot; &quot;rs10000023&quot; &quot;rs10000030&quot; &quot;rs1000007&quot; ... $ CHR : int [1:306102] 4 4 4 2 4 4 16 4 2 4 ... $ BP : int [1:306102] 21227772 95952929 103593179 237416793 21504615 157793485 24325037 33810744 235355721 77575270 ... $ A1 : chr [1:306102] &quot;C&quot; &quot;T&quot; &quot;A&quot; &quot;C&quot; ... $ A2 : chr [1:306102] &quot;T&quot; &quot;G&quot; &quot;G&quot; &quot;T&quot; ... $ MAF : num [1:306102] 0.426 0.484 0.162 0.312 0.343 ... $ callrate: num [1:306102] 0.999 0.989 0.998 1 0.991 ... $ NMISS : int [1:306102] 3996 3957 3991 4000 3963 3919 3899 3931 3927 3941 ... $ NCHROBS : int [1:306102] 7992 7914 7982 8000 7926 7838 7798 7862 7854 7882 ... $ BETA : num [1:306102] 0.04114 -0.00985 -0.02235 0.01784 -0.07904 ... $ SE : num [1:306102] 0.0457 0.0456 0.0605 0.0489 0.0471 ... $ OR : num [1:306102] 1.042 0.99 0.978 1.018 0.924